The relationship between sets established by ⊆ is called "inclusion" or "containment", and is given also for equal sets, that is, equality of sets is the same as mutual containment in each other: "A" ⊆ "B" and "B" ⊆ "A" is equivalent to "A" = "B".
There is a unique set with no members, called the "empty set" (or the "null set"), which is denoted by the symbol ∅ (other notations are used; see empty set).
